453":"1453","1386":"1386","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","St Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Tetbury, Gloucestershire, England":"Tetbury, Gloucestershire, England","Winterbourne, Berkshire, England":"Winterbourne, Berkshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Of Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Winterbourne, Gloucestershire, England":"Winterbourne, Gloucestershire, England","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stephens","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Stevens  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stevens","meanings":["English (London), Flemish, Dutch, and North German: patronymic from the personal name   Steven  . The surname of Flemish origin is also found in the Walloon part of Belgium. In North America, the English form of the surname has also absorbed some like-sounding Jewish names and various other European cognates, e.g. Greek   Stefanidis  , Serbian <b>Stevanović</b> (see   Stevanovic  ), Slovenian and Slovak <b>Štefanič</b> (see   Stefanic  )."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Fitz","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Either a short form of any of the numerous names representing a transferred use of a surname formed with the Anglo-Norman French prefix <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son of ’, as for example   Fitzgerald  ,   Fitzroy  , or a transferred use of the surname <i>Fitz</i>, which may be of the same derivation, but applied originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same given name, or a local name from Fitz in Shropshire, named with the Old English personal name <i>Fitt</i> + <i>hōh</i> ‘hill spur’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":1,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":14,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":23,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":68,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Fitz Stephens III was born about 1314, in Gloucestershire, England, his father, John Fitz Stephens II, was 33 and his mother, Margaret de Berkeley, was 29. He married Joanna Spelly in 1346, in Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1386, in his hometown, at the age of 73, and was buried in Tetbury, Gloucestershire, England."},"et":{"about 1314–1386":"umbes 1314–1386","1314–1386":"